## Description
The **Route Files **task allows to redirect files based on the configured file pattern rule (regex).

For example, this task can sort incoming documents based on their file extension, for example routing all XML files (*.xml) to branch A and plain text files (*.txt ) to branch B.

> **Task behavior in case of no output**

Route Files will not fail if no output chunk is produced.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

## Configuration
**![](data:image/png;base64,)**

- In the **Alias **field, enter the name of the task that will be displayed in the workflow.

- In the **Output Branches **section, click ![](data:image/png;base64,) (**Add**) and fill in the required fields to add a new branch:

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Enter the **Name **of the new branch.

- Activate the **All other files **flag to use this branch for all file patterns which are not covered by other branch configurations. When co nfigured, this branch acts as the "else" branch and is always triggered.

> Important

When this option is activated, only the **Disposition **field can be configured for this branch. In the list of **Branches**, this branch receives the **else **flag to visually indicate that it's the catch-all branch.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

- In the **Trigger **field, enter the filename pattern to trigger this branch, while all other files from the previous task are redirected to all branches.

- In the **Filters **field, enter one or more filename patterns to filter the files that must be routed to this branch (for example: *.csv).

- In the **Disposition **field, select the preferred behavior of the branch:

**Single fork**: Trigger a single instance of the following task in the workflow (treating the incoming files as a single chunk).

- **Multiple forks**: Trigger multiple instances of the following task in the workflow (one for each input file).

> Note

This option is useful, for example, when multiple instances of the Transform Files (DT) task should be triggered after the Unpack Files (one instance for each file).
